title: Draft:Otis Allan Glazebrook
content:
Born: October 13, 1850, Richmond, Virginia, U.S.
Died: September 26, 1921, New York City, New York, U.S.


= Biography =
Otis Allen Glazebrook was an American Episcopal priest and the primary founder of the Alpha Tau Omega (ATO) fraternity. Born in Richmond, Virginia, in 1850, Glazebrook attended the Virginia Military Institute (VMI), where he conceived the idea of establishing a fraternity that would help heal the sectional wounds inflicted by the Civil War. In 1865, alongside Alfred Marshall and Erskine Mayo Ross, he founded Alpha Tau Omega at VMI, emphasizing Christian brotherhood.After graduating from VMI in 1867, Glazebrook pursued theological studies and was ordained as an Episcopal priest. He served in various capacities within the church, including rectorships in several states and chaplaincies in educational institutions. His commitment to the church and education was evident throughout his life.


= Contributions to Alpha Tau Omega =
As a founder of ATO, Glazebrook played a critical role in shaping the fraternity's principles and expanding its presence across the United States. His vision for a brotherhood transcending the post-war divides was instrumental in fostering a sense of unity among young men during a period of national reconstruction.


= Legacy =
Otis Allen Glazebrook's impact on American collegiate life and the Episcopal Church is remembered for his pioneering role in creating a fraternal organization that promoted reconciliation and moral integrity. His works and the values he instilled in Alpha Tau Omega continue to influence generations of young men. Glazebrook died in 1921 in New York City and was commemorated for his contributions to both his fraternity and his faith.: October 13, 1850, Richmond, Virginia, U.S.
Died: September 26, 1921, New York City, New York, U.S.

title: Order of the Arrow ceremonies and symbols
content:
The Order of the Arrow relies heavily on ceremonies and symbols. While the content of the ceremonies are secret and protected by the Order of the Arrow, the requirement to take part in these ceremonies are made publicly available by the Society.


== Ceremonies ==


=== Unit Election ===
Elections are held in the unit and organized by the Lodge. Members of the unit are invited to vote for those who best follow the Scout Oath and Law. Campaigning is not allowed and voting is done by secret ballot. All active members are entitled to vote and to be elected, a scout mist receive votes on at least half of the ballots submitted. Voting a blank ballot is considered voting against all the members on the ballot.
To be eligible for election, a youth must:

be a registered member of the Boy Scouts of America
have spent at least 15 days and nights camping within the last two years including one long-term camp consisting of at least five consecutive nights
be under the age of 21
hold the Scouts BSA First Class rank, the Venturing Discovery Award, or the Sea Scout Ordinary rank or higher, be approved by their unit leader and be elected by the youth members of their unit.
Adults aged 21 or older may be nominated after meeting the camping requirements and being approved by the lodge adult selection committee.


=== Call-Out or Tapout ===

Prior to Indiction, a Call-Out Ceremony (also known as tapout) takes place. This is a public ceremony that officially recognizes scouts that have been elected to be candidates for membership in the Order of the Arrow. This is an opportunity for the Lodges who organize it to present the OA to all the scouts present, its history, recognize the candidates and challenge the scouts who are not elected to strive to uphold the Scouting ideals with the hope of one day being selected. This ceremony is usually short, impressive and is made to allow all present to understand the importance of the Order of the Arrow membership.


=== Induction (Ordeal) ===

After being elected or nominated, candidates may participate in a call-out ceremony to recognize those Scouts and Scouters that were selected before they attend their Ordeal. The call-out ceremony may be performed at summer camp, a camporee, a call-out weekend or at a unit meeting. Candidates subsequently participate in the induction ceremony called the Ordeal, intended to emphasize service and selflessness. During the induction, "candidates maintain complete silence, receive small amounts of food, work on camp improvement projects, and are required to sleep alone, apart from other campers, which teaches significant values." If they succeed in their ordeal the candidates are then welcomed as Ordeal members in a formal Ordeal Ceremony.


=== Brotherhood ===
Ordeal members are entitled to all the same rights and privileges of membership in the Order as Brotherhood and Vigil Honor members—there are no ranks within the Order. However, moving on to Brotherhood membership offers an opportunity to reaffirm one's commitment to the Order. Arrowmen may "seal" their membership after six months by demonstrating their knowledge of the traditions and obligations of the OA. They then participate in an induction ceremony and become Brotherhood members.
While the Ordeal consists primarily of physical impressions, "the Brotherhood ceremony is one of the deeper and quieter mental impressions."


=== Vigil Honor ===

The Vigil Honor is a recognition given to Arrowmen for distinguished contributions beyond the immediate responsibilities of their position or office to their lodge, the Order of the Arrow, Scouting, or their Scout Camp. The Vigil Honor may be conferred upon Arrowmen who have completed a minimum of two years as a Brotherhood member and have performed exceptional service above and beyond their immediate responsibilities through leadership, exemplary efforts, and dedication. However, under no circumstances should tenure in Scouting or the Order of the Arrow be considered as reason enough for a Vigil Honor recommendation. Selection is annual and is limited to one person for every 50 members of the lodge, and members of the Order can be inducted into the Vigil Honor only with the written approval of the National Order of the Arrow Committee.
As a part of the Vigil Honor induction, each new Vigil Honor member is given a Vigil Honor name in the language of the Lenni Lenape or the language of their local Lodge. An English translation of the Vigil Honor name is also provided, and the name often represents a characteristic of the individual.

Order of the Arrow ceremonies were once considered to be secret, and consequently, the OA has been viewed by some as a secret society. With the introduction of Youth Protection program guidelines in 1980s, the BSA has made clear that any concerned parent, guardian, or religious leader may view a video of the ceremonies, attend meetings, or read ceremonial texts upon request to a council, district, lodge, or chapter official to assure themselves that there is nothing objectionable. Such persons are asked to safeguard (conceal) the details relating to ceremonies for the sake of the participants. The intent of the provision for parents and religious leaders to be allowed access to ceremonies is to ensure that there is no religious conflict or violations of youth protection guidelines occurring. Parents have long been discouraged in many Lodges from seizing the opportunity to use the provision for photo opportunities with their sons, and some lodges have instituted bans on photography during the ceremonies. Hazing or demeaning initiation pranks are also prohibited by the OA and the BSA.


=== Paper Copies ===
There is no known written copy of the ritual used for the 1915 Treasure Island camping season. However, a few details are known, based on later testimonies. The first inductees were Robert Craig and Gilpin Allen who were inducted on July 16, 2015, and wore a black sash for the ceremony. E. Urner Goodman wore a black robe (similar to a graduation gown) with triangular badges on it with a black tortoise superimposed on the white triangle. He was the Chief of the Fire. Carroll Edson also wore a black robe similar to Goodman's with a white tortoise shaped badge on his chest. He was the Sachem. Harry A. Yoder, a staffer who had assisted in the construction of the fire guided the entire camp to the new campfire circle. He was however not a ceremonialist in the Frist Ceremony.
The first written Ordeal Ceremony was written in 1921 along with the formation of the Grand Lodge. It was mimeographed on Letter size paper and distributed to the Supreme Chief of the Fire of each member lodge. Some changes were also introduced there:

Water was to be applied to the left bared breast to symbolize the cleansing of the candidate from selfishness and evil
A root-stock was to be chewed to symbolize the increase in strength and vigor to be used in the service of others.
The format was changed in 1927. It became a 24 pages 5"x7" booklet folded vertically. This format remained in place until 1998 when it was changed to an 8 1/2 x 11 booklet. In the booklet, the Pre-Ordeal Ceremony and the Ordeal Ceremony could be found along with the Legend in poetic form. The Brotherhood Ceremony was made in a booklet only in 1936 remaining a mimeographed document until then.
In the 2015 Edition of the Order of the Arrow Handbook, it is mentioned that non-members of the Order of the Arrow should not attend ceremonies but that it recognizes and respects the right of adults such as parents, Scout leaders or religious leader to have questions about the ceremony. The lodge adviser or his representative can discuss the content of the ceremony and concernes brought by the adult enquiring and that the adult will maintain the confidentiality of the ceremony. If questions remain unanswered, the adult will be permitted to read the text of the ceremony. Parents are allowed to refuse that their child take part in the ceremony and therefore that they join the Order of the Arrow.
The ceremonies utilize symbolic settings, rites, and principles to convey various Scouting ideals to participants. "The values of the Order of the Arrow, 'a brotherhood of cheerful service,' were passed on during a night-time ceremony: an arrowhead outlined with stones on the ground, candles on the stones, a huge bonfire at the base of the arrowhead, and at the point of the arrow a lectern from which was read, and danced, the story of heroic sacrifice for others."


== Symbols ==


=== Degree/Honor Symbols ===


==== White Sash ====


===== Evolution =====
Originally, the Sashes were called arrow bands. These bands were described as being in the original ceremony a black band with a white vertical stripe on the front made of the same material as black academic robes based on testimonies of early members. In the Ritual of the Second Degree (published around 1918 by Dr. William Hinkle), the band was moved from the right shoulder to the left shoulder right before the end of the ceremony. The same band was worn by First Degree (Ordeal) and Second Degree (Brotherhood) but on different shoulders. The earliest photographic evidence from 1919 from Treasure Island confirms that the bands were worn on both shoulders. No original sashes are known to exist today. This information comes from two testimonies from early members. According to Harry Yoder, the first guide and charter member of the Order wrote in 1921: "In the early days of the Order the members wore a black sash with a white stripe running lengthwise instead of the white band with the red arrow." George Chapman recounted in the unpublished work The Arrow and the Vigil (1953): "As has been previously mentioned, the officers of Wimachtendienk wore black robes for the induction ceremony. Members wore a black sash with a white arrow on it, very similar to the sash worn today except for the color."

A black and white picture published in August 1921 in a Philadelphia newspaper on the Wimachtendienk shows the officers wearing black robes with a white band and a dark-colored arrow on top. It is unclear if that arrow was black or red. In 1921, when the Grand Lodge was formed, a picture was also taken showing members wearing the band on both left and right shoulder. It also shows Goodman and Edson wearing a sash in the shape of a triangle on the chest that appears to be a fraternal bib. This was the Third Degree bib-type sash. The first known physical examples of the white sash with a red arrow dates back from around 1922. First Degree and Second Degree had a white wool-felt band with red wool-felt arrows sewn on it. The Vigil Honor had a white wool-felt band without an arrow and a red Vigil triangle with arrows on each side. These were made by the Grand Lodge and remained mainly unchanged from 1921 to 1948. Region 7 however used bands made of twill cloth with arrows in red linen from the late 1920s to the mid-1930s.

In 1948, the Order retained the white wool-felt for the band but the red arrow was flocked silk-screened on it. The Vigil Honor had a large red wool-felt triangle with the white arrows silk-screened. In 1950, it was decided that the sash would go on the right shoulder only. The sash changed again: Brotherhood bars were flocked onto the sashed to distinguish Ordeal from Brotherhood. In 1951/1952, the Vigil oversized triangle was replaced by a small triangle. All the sashes used the same silk-screening process and were all the same size.
In 1955, the wool-felt was replaced with twill material and the silk-screen was replaced by embroidery. The Sash had two plies of material so the embroidery did not show through. Over the years, the stitching on the edge evolved but the sash remained the same. The arrows on the Vigil Honor triangle were manufactured both counterclockwise as well as clockwise. In 1988, the arrows and other red symbols were hot ironed on the sash. This was short lived as the sashes did not survive the wash and by 1990, the sashes were embroidered again. It has remained unchanged to this day.


==== Today ====
At formal events or Order of the Arrow functions, Arrowmen can be readily identified by a white sash bearing a red arrow that is worn over their right shoulder. An Ordeal member wears a sash with a lone arrow. The Brotherhood member wears a sash bearing an arrow with a red bar at each end of the arrow. A Vigil Honor member wears a sash with the same bars of as the Brotherhood sash at each end of the arrow, and a Vigil Honor triangle on the center of the shaft. The OA sash is not worn at the same time as the merit badge sash, nor worn folded in the belt. The sash as a form of recognition dates to the founding of the Order and has a long history of changes in usage and design.
It is not to be worn at Troop Meetings, Campouts, Courts of Honor, Training and FOS Presentations as it is a symbol of the OA ideal, not a rank of an item to "show off" your honor. It is appropriate to wear it at events where OA business is taking place such as Unit Election, Lodge Fellowship, Lodge Meetings, etc.


==== Ribbon ====

The early pins were replaced by the ribbon. However, the ribbon does not indicate the Honor of the wearer, only the membership to the OA and only the sash references the Honor today.
Order members may choose to wear the OA Universal Ribbon also known as "Dangles" suspended from the right uniform shirt pocket button.
The Ribbon was introduced in 1942. This was the first time Arrowmen could officially wear the OA symbol. It was very similar to the current version and was made of red and white silk with a sterling arrow. The first arrows pointed left instead of right, pointing left over the wearer's shoulder. In 1950, the OA removed the code words referencing "left" and replaced it with "right". In 1952, the ribbon also switched to point over the wearer's right shoulder.
Additional award pins can be attached to the ribbon including the Order of the Arrow 75th Anniversary Achievement from 1990 and the Order of the Arrow Arrowman Service Award Ribbon Pin issued between January 1, 2001, and December 31, 2003.


==== Other Symbolism ====
Arrowmen also exchange a special handshake as a token of brotherhood, along with other signs and passwords. A signature acronym, WWW (Wimachtendienk Wingolauchsik Witahemui – Brotherhood of Cheerful Service), is often depicted in publications, regalia, etc.


=== Lodge Symbols ===


==== Totem Pins ====
Since the Order of the Arrow was founded as a fraternal organization, it followed similar traditions similar to its counterparts. These organizations often used small pins made of precious metals as insignias. In Article III of the first constitution of the Order of the Arrow from 1916, three recognition pieces are described:

a silver arrow pledge for candidates (now Ordeal)*
a gold tortoise and arrow pin for First Degree (now Brotherhood)*
a gold tortoise and triangle for Second Degree (now Vigil)*
*The Ordeal in 1916 was considered a pledge and not a full membership. Therefore, there were only two degrees.
The pledge (Ordeal) pin is almost identical to the silver arrow pin still found today except it is now die-struck as opposed to poured into a die.
These pins were mandatory in the beginning of the order. However, due to the cost of the silver and gold used in their manufacturing, these pins were not always manufactured by the Lodges. The pins were made by several jewelers over the years. The use of pins became optional. These pins were not to be worn on the sash or on the BSA uniform but only on civilian clothes.
The Grand Lodge Insignia Committee required that each lodge have its own distinct totem in a similar way as the heraldry rule that no two coats of arms can be the same. The idea was that members could determine the status and local affiliation of another member just by looking at their pin while non-members would be clueless of the meaning of the pin. By 1930, the requirement for each Lodge to have its own totem became impractical due to the number of Lodges being created.
These were the ancestors of the current Lodge Pocket Flap Patches. These pins were used along with the Ribbon after it was introduced in 1942. Some lodges still make these pins but they are rare.


==== Lodge Pocket Flaps Patches ====

In a 1938 National Meeting at Camp Irondale, Missouri, shows several arrowmen wearing lodges patches of different shapes. These patches were a deviation from the national uniform standard at the time. However, this practice would become mainstream and official. It would replace the Early Lodge Pins. Indeed, a pin could cost upward of $4.50 while a lodge patch could be purchased for 20 cents. Finally, in 1945, the BSA Uniform Committee agreed to the use of the Lodge Patch. However, it was omitted from the 1948 Order of the Arrow Handbook. The use of the lodge patch was advocated in the handbook but it did not indicate that it had to be worn on the right pocket. As a result, each lodge had its own way of placing the patches. It was the Ajapeu Lodge in Doylstown, PA around 1942 that had the right shirt pocket flap as the OA location.
It took until 1954 for the national OA committee finally offered clarification with the following decision:
"It is strongly recommended by the National Committee that these emblems be made to fit the shape of the right shirt pocket flap. The right shirt pocket flap has been approved by the National Committee on Badges and Insignia for official Order of the Arrow Insignia where the other emblems are only temporary insignia when used on the uniform. It should be realized that this is a great advantage and a complement to the Order of the Arrow."
OA membership and Lodge affiliation are indicated by the wearing of the lodge emblem (commonly known as a lodge flap), an embroidered patch is worn on the right pocket flap of the uniform shirt. Each lodge flap has a unique design, generally reflecting the name, geography or history of the lodge. Part of this is a totem that represents the lodge. The flap was officially approved by the National Committee in 1954. No other organization has received the honor from Boy Scouts of America to have a portion of the uniform reserved for their own use. Special issues of flaps are created to commemorate anniversaries and other events, and are a popular item for those who engage in Scouting memorabilia collecting.
The Lodge Flap has over time grown and today many Lodge Flaps are actually two patches: one for the flap and one for the pocket itself. Since 2007 with Operations Update 07–8, Lodges can not create flaps that are larger than the flap itself. The two part sets comply with the guidelines if they are made of two separate pieces, the two parts can be worn independently from one another and the flap patch stays within the boundaries of the pocket flap.


=== National Bonnets ===
In 1938, a bonnet made was made by members of the Anicus Lodge of Golden eagle feathers in the fashion of a Native American War bonnet. It was gifted to the National Lodge of the OA in 1940 to be worn by the chief of the National Lodge. It would be used for over 40 years for the opening and closing shows of NOAC as well as National Planning Meetings and other national events.
Since 1918 with the Migratory Bird Treaty Act, the Federal Government had started protected birds and slowly restricting the use of some bird feathers and other body parts. In 1940, the Bald Eagle Protection Act was past protecting Bald Eagles exclusively. This Act would be extended to the Golden Eagle in 1962. This is law is enforced by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (USFWS). On January 1, 1976, with the encouragement of the USFWS the National OA Committee issued its "Protected Feather Clarification" policy prohibited the use of animal parts in the construction of Native American regalia used at Scouting events. The USFWS made an allowance for the use of the bonnet and it continued to be used after that date.
In November 1980, a fire destroyed BSA's National Office where the bonnet was on display and it was destroyed. The National OA Committee announced it would construct two replacement bonnets. For the first time, the national vice chief would also wear a bonnet. Various options were proposed to complete this while also complying with the Law. Eventually, the solution came from the USFWS itself. After confirming that the original bonnet was made of real eagle feathers obtained prior to the enactment of the laws, approval was granted to replace the original bonnet with two bonnets. Each was made of 32 real golden eagle feathers tipped with owl feathers provided by the USFWS. The feathers came from illegal bonnets confiscated by USFWS and were offered to BSA/OA by the Federal agency via a special permit/loan agreement for scientific and educational purposes. The replacement were first starting in 1982 and used until 2004.
In keeping with its policy on Protected Feathers, the bonnets were retired and replaced with new replica bonnets using imitation eagle feathers. These bonnets were first used in 2005.

title: Ellwood-Zimmerman House
content:
The Ellwood-Zimmerman House was an iconic mid-century modern house designed by Craig Ellwood built in Brentwood, Los Angeles, California in 1950. It was demolished, to much criticism, in 2024.


== History ==
The Zimmerman House was a low-slung, 2,770 square-foot, five-bedroom, three bathroom home. The non-profit group, USModernist, states that Martin and Eva Zimmerman commissioned the home in 1949.  The Zimmerman's sold the home to Richard Kelton in 1968, following that it was sold in 1975 to Hilda and Sam Rolfe for $205,000.
In 2022, the home was purchased for $12.5 million by actor, Chris Pratt and his wife Katherine Schwarzenegger who had it bulldozed to make way to build a 15,000 square foot mansion. The destruction of the home has been viewed as a systemic problem where older mid-century homes of significant historic value are seen as less valuable than the plot of land they occupy.


== Description ==
The Zimmerman House was an early work by Ellwood. The Zimmerman House was exemplary of the California modernist style indicative of Ellwood, and other architects of the time such as Charles and Ray Eames, Pierre Koenig and Richard Neutra. Garrett Eckbo designed the home's garden which was also destroyed.
The one-story home was known for it's light-filled openness, featuring many sliding glass doors that provided views and passage into the garden. Similar to Ellwood's, Lappin House, the home was designed and arranged with a spine corridor, and featured a free-standing centrally-located brick fireplace that separated the living room area from the dining room, similar to Case Study House 9 designed by Charles Eames and Eero Saarinen. Progressive Architecture magazine published a feature story on the home, and was considered a "showpiece" that was featured in other architectural magazines as well. The home was located at 400 North Carmelina Avenue in the Brentwood neighborhood. The Los Angeles Conservancy stated that at the time of demolition, the home was "highly intact and a noteworthy example of modernist design from this era." The façade of the structure featured recessed glazing creating a space, as described by Progressive Architecture as "completely open to the lawn and vistas to the rear." Arts & Archtecture magazine described the façade as "four ten-foot glass doors, each sliding, open (to the) living-dining area to the terrace of textured concrete which leads to the plant garden. The bedrooms alternate on either side of the spine.
The home was described by Ellwood's daughter, Erin Ellwood, an Ojai, California-based interior designer, as a "time capsule."


== References ==


== Further reading ==
Erin Ellwood, Michael Boyd. Making L.A. Modern: Craig Ellwood - Myth, Man, Designer, Rizzoli Publishers (2018) ISBN 9780847861538

title: Dapaong Solar Power Station
content:
The Dapaong Solar Power Station is a planned 25 megawatts solar power plant in Togo. In April 2024, the Government of Togo announced an international tender for qualified international firms and consortia to submit bids of expression of interest in the design, procurement and installation of a 25 MW solar power plant, with attached battery storage power station (BESS) storage of 40MWh. The tender closes on 4 June 2024.


== Location ==
The power station would be located in the town of Dapaong, the capital city of Savanes Region, in the extreme north of the country, near the international border with Burkina Faso. Dapaong is located approximately 613 kilometres (381 mi), north of the central business district of the city of Lome, the national capital and the country's largest city.


== Overview ==
Before 2024, a larger solar farm with generation capacity of 30 MW was envisaged. The successful EPC bidder will design a 25 MW solar photovoltaic plant with an attached 40 MWh BESS and a connected transmission and distribution network. The electricity is intended for distribution to about 60 locations in Savanes Region, servicing 600,000 to 700,000 Togolese customers.


== Other considerations ==
The construction of this solar farm is part of a World Bank-supported regional energy infrastructure development project. The US$311 million "Regional Emergency Solar Power Intervention Project" (RESPITE), covers the countries of Sierra Leone, Chad, Liberia, and Togo. It is also part of Togo's national program "Emergency Resilience Building Program in the Savanes Region" (PURS).

List of power stations in Togo
Blitta Solar Power Station

title: Antisemitism in Columbia University
content:
Antisemitism in Columbia University was prevalent in the first half of the 20th century and resurged in the early 21st century. In 1920 Columbia University was the first American university to initiate quotas on Jews, halving the Jewish student population in two years. In the early 21st century and acutely after the October 7 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel, students and staff protests and commentary were criticized as antisemitic and scrutinized by the US Congress, which opened an investigation on Columbia University. In April 2024, Columbia University President Minouche Shafik condemned antisemitic acts by students and faculty in campus and said the university was in a "moral crisis". United States president Joe Biden and the mayor of New York, Eric Adams condemned the 2024 anti-Israel protests as antisemitic and condemned the calls for violence and harassment against Jews.  


== 20th century ==
During the 20th century American anti-Jewish sentiment was common in America, and American universities imposed quotas on Jews in order to restrict the number of Jews in universities. Such efforts first began in Columbia University. New York City, in which Columbia University is situated in the early 20th century had a population that was. In 1920, Columbia University had a 40% Jewish enrollment rate according to Oliver Pollak.
Since most Jewish students at the time were came from poor families they had to work night jobs in order to pay their tuition and also lived at home to save money. Therefore, Columbia required students to live in dormitories in campus as well as limiting scholarships in order to limit the number of Jewish students who could afford to study in the university. Columbia also began to conduct interviews in admissions process and according to Mark Oppenheimer university representatives detected accents or telling signs of Jewish origin if the name of the applicant wasn't clearly Jewish. According to Nadell, elite Protestants students began to abandon Columbia due to its changing culture, after the initiation of the program Columbia halved the number of Jewish students within two years (1920–22).
In the early 20th century some school administrators held anti-Jewish beliefs which rationalized by them and that their sentiment was based on social reality. In 1903, dean of Columbia wrote that “What most people regard as a racial problem is really a social problem.”.


== 21st century ==

Following the October 7 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel, Joseph Massad a Columbia University professor in Middle Eastern, South Asian and African studies said that the attack on Israel, in which 1200 Israelis were killed including civilians, was a "resistance offensive" and "awesome". President Shafik condemned his comment in April 2024 and said he was under investigation, also saying Massad no longer has a leadership role in the university. InsideHigherEd reported however that in the 2024-24 Academic year Massad chaired an academic review panel in the college of the arts and sciences.
Following the October 7 attack, Mohamed Abdou, a visiting scholar who had said that he sides with Hamas and Islamic Jihad was hired by the university. In April 2024, President Minouche Shafik said Abdou was on his way out of the university.
Katherine Franke a professor of law in Columbia said that all students who have served in the IDF are dangerous and shouldn't be allowed on campus.
A task force on antisemitism was created by the university in late 2023.  
The university was sued by Jewish students which said that in the university “mobs of pro-Hamas students and faculty march by the hundreds shouting vile antisemitic slogans, including calls to genocide.”
In a hearing before Congress in April 2024, Columbia University president Minouche Shafik condemned antisemitism and said that "from the river to the sea" is antisemitic. Professors in the university were under investigation according to the president for antisemitic remarks. Shafik said that dozens of students were disciplined and that Columbia University is in a "moral crisis".
During anti-Israel protests, some students called for intifada and urged Hamas brigades to kill Israeli soldiers. Additionally, there were calls to burn Tel Aviv, a major Israeli city known for its liberal culture. Anti-Israel activists sang songs in support of Hamas and chanted slogans expressing solidarity with the organization. The Palestine Solidarity Working Group defended militancy and praised Hamas's attacks against Israel. Anti-Israel protestors also made derogatory remarks towards Jewish students, telling them to "Go back to Europe" and taunting them with calls of "Jews" and "Go back to Poland".
Jewish students reported feeling unsafe, being spat on, and expressed relief at leaving the university. They felt their grievances were not adequately represented by student representatives. One protestor threatened Jewish students, stating, "The 7th of October is going to be every day for you!". Some of the anti-Israel protestors also chanted "From the water to the war (a reference to the Jordan river and the Mediterranean), Palestine is Arab" which is considered a call for the cleansing of the region from Jews and the denial of Jewish rights for self sovereignty in their ancestral homeland.
Journalist Seth Mandel argued that universities were promoting the idea that Jews should be displaced from their homes because they belong to a race that supposedly belongs elsewhere, citing incidents at Columbia University as an example. The Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP) and the Workers Organizing for Liberation (WOL) both advocated for the destruction of Israel and the targeting of Jewish Israelis, and played a role in organizing the protests at Columbia University.
The President of the United States, Joe Biden condemned the protests saying “Even in recent days, we’ve seen harassment and calls for violence against Jews. This blatant antisemitism is reprehensible and dangerous – and it has absolutely no place on college campuses, or anywhere in our country.”
The protestors responded by saying they were peaceful and distanced themselves from non student protestors.  The mayor of New York said he was “horrified and disgusted with the antisemitism being spewed at and around the Columbia University campus.” And increased police presence around campus.
Shai Davidai, a prominent Israeli Jewish professor in Columbia University was barred from entering the main campus. Davidai is a supporter of Jewish students rights on US campuses,. Columbia University's COO said this was done to maintain community safety. Davidai wrote on X formerly known as Twitter "To the best of my knowledge, the last time that a professor was denied access to their own university for being Jewish was Nazi Germany". Davidai also said that Columbia University could not allow him to enter because they could not protect his safety as a Jewish professor. Davidai accused the university of being unable to stand up against anti-Israel protestors which had been condemned as antisemitic by US president Joe Biden; Davidai called the anti-Israel protest a "Pro-Hamas mob".
Following the incident, Robert Kraft, owner of the "patriots" team said he would stop donating to the university due to its inability to keep Jewish students safe and was saddened by the hatred growing in campus and the country.
Due to the intensity of anti-Israel protests, Columbia University allowed students to take classes and exams virtually.  Rep. Virginia Foxx, chair of the United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce, warned Columbia University that the failure of Columbia to ensure safety was In violation of the university's Title VI obligations, on which is conditioned federal assistance to the university. 
Rabbi Elie Buechler who is linked to Columbia University's Orthodox Union Jewish Learning Initiative urged Jewish students to remain home or return home due to safety concerns.


== See also ==
Antisemitism in US Higher Education


== References ==

title: Qatari influence in Europe
content:
Qatari influence in Europe refers to Qatar's efforts to influence the culture and policies of European countries. This influence is achieved through strategic investments, lobbying, academic and cultural initiatives, and a prominent presence in European sports, primarily financed by the wealth of the royal family. These activities have been pioneered under the leadership of Emir Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani, gradually increasing Qatar's power as part of a broader strategy to diversify their influence.
Qatar's ownership of Al Jazeera has given it a powerful tool to influence public opinion in Europe and beyond. The network's coverage of global events, including those in the Middle East, has been both praised for its breadth and criticized for perceived biases, promotion of Islamist positions, and inciting terrorism. Qatar has been depicted as pursuing an Islamist agenda in its foreign policy, especially following the Arab Spring. Critics argue that Qatar's investments and cultural initiatives are part of a broader agenda to extend its influence and potentially spread its ideological views.
Qatar has a substantial involvement in European sports, and the country is integrated in many aspects of the sports value chain. This involvement has been described as a form of "sportswashing," a strategy aimed at enhancing its global image through sports. Qatar's strategy differs from historical examples from Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany, who also used mega-events to showcase national strength, by focusing instead on sports commentary, partnerships with major brands, and ownership of local sports clubs to enhance its influence.
Qatar's involvement in Europe has sparked controversy, marked by allegations of corruption and influence-peddling. Incidents such as "Qatargate" have emerged, along with accusations of financing and providing political cover for groups like Hamas, Hezbollah, and the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria (ISIS). In addition, Numerous sources accused Qatar of allocating millions of dollars to Muslim Brotherhood activities in Europe and financially supporting the Muslim Brotherhood in France, the United Kingdom, Italy and Denmark, with more than $175 million over the years. According to European statistical data, “Qatar Charity is one of the main supporters of Islamic groups in Europe, donating money to 60% of Islamic institutions, including charities, relief programmes, Quranic schools and mosques”.


== Background ==
Qatar's relations with Europe traces back to the early 20th century. The initial contact between Qatar and European countries were primarily driven by trade, with the Gulf region serving as a crucial node in the maritime routes connecting the East and the West. During the colonial era, European powers, notably the British Empire, established protectorates across the Middle East. In the case of Qatar, it became a British protectorate in the early 20th century. This period laid the groundwork for modern statehood in Qatar and introduced European political and legal systems, albeit in a context of external control and influence.
The discovery of oil in Qatar in 1940, followed by the development of its vast natural gas reserves in the latter half of the 20th century, marked a turning point in Qatar's international relations. Europe's growing energy needs led to increased engagement with Qatar, which quickly transformed into one of the world's leading exporters of liquefied natural gas (LNG).
Qatar gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1971. In the decades that followed, Qatar leveraged its hydrocarbon resources to develop its economy, gradually increasing its global presence and influence, including in Europe. This led to significant Qatari investments in Europe across various sectors, including finance, real estate, sports, and media. Such investments were not only economic in nature but also served to forge strategic alliances and enhance Qatar's influence on the global stage.
The establishment of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) in 1981, which includes Qatar and other Gulf nations, provided a new framework for regional cooperation and interaction with external partners, including the European Union (EU). In 2018, the EU-Qatar Cooperation Arrangement was signed, providing a structured framework for political dialogue and sectoral cooperation.
Education City in Qatar was established in 1997 by the Qatar Foundation for Education, Science and Community Development. This initiative was part of a vision to enhance education and research in the region, promoting Qatar's development into a hub for academic excellence on an international scale. Universities from the UK, France and the Netherland opened campuses in Qatar, offering programs in fields ranging from museum studies to business administration. These institutions attract students from around the world, leveraging Qatar's stature and its investments in education to serve as a bridge between Western and Eastern educational practices. The involvement of European schools in Qatar has not been without controversy. For example, UCL became the first British university to open a campus in ‘Education City’ in 2012. But in 2014, Dame Nicola Brewer, UCL's International Vice-Provost, said that the university should reevaluate its engagements in Qatar, taking into account the new political circumstances. This was in response to the transition of power in 2013, where Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad became the Emir.
In 2005, the Qatar Investment Authority (QIA), was established by the Qatari government as a sovereign wealth fund. Its primary purpose is to manage the surplus revenue from Qatar's oil and natural gas exports. The creation of the QIA was part of a broader strategy to diversify Qatar's economy away from its traditional reliance on hydrocarbon sectors. The QIA was endowed with a large amount of capital to invest internationally. This fund quickly grew in size, becoming one of the world's largest sovereign wealth funds, with assets worth hundreds of billions of dollars and major investments in European markets, including real estate purchases and stakes in key industries.
In 2017, a blockade on Qatar was initiated by Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt, who severed diplomatic and trade ties with Qatar. These nations accused Qatar of supporting terrorism, particularly pointing to its alleged backing of groups like the Muslim Brotherhood and its perceived close relations with Iran. They also criticized Qatar's independent foreign policy and the influential role of its global media outlet, Al Jazeera. In response, Qatar denied the allegations, asserting its commitment to fighting terrorism and sought to bolster its own economic independence and diplomatic ties. The blockade on Qatar was lifted in January 2021.
In the wake of the Qatar diplomatic crisis, Qatar faced a complex geopolitical challenge when US President Donald Trump appeared to support the blockade against them. Recognizing the potential vulnerability, Qatar perceived a need to diversify its international alliances and reduce its geopolitical risk. Thus, Qatar turned its focus towards Europe, aiming to cultivate deeper ties with influential European nations such as the UK, France, and Germany.
Economic investments were central to Qatar's approach to strengthen ties with European nations. The QIA had already been actively investing in significant European sectors such as automotive, construction, and finance. For example, major companies like Volkswagen and Siemens, reflecting a longstanding economic relationship that was further solidified during the crisis. In addition, Qatar increased its role in Europe's energy security, becoming a crucial supplier of LNG to several European countries, thus embedding itself as a key player in Europe's energy landscape. These strategic moves not only diversified Qatar's international relations but also enhanced its economic security and political leverage in Europe.


== Economic Influence ==

Qatar's economic influence has been both broad and significant, reflecting a strategic approach to diversify its investment portfolio beyond the traditional energy sector, reflecting the Gulf state's strategic deployment of its considerable financial resources to achieve both economic growth and geopolitical power. These investments span various industries, including finance, real estate, sports, and technology, and have had a considerable impact on the economic ties between Qatar and European countries. Qatar has been accused of leveraging its economic resources to expand its influence on the global stage.


=== Energy sector ===
Qatar's initial engagement with the European market commenced in the energy sector, where it utilized its substantial natural gas reserves to establish itself as a significant player. The country secured long-term contracts to supply liquefied natural gas (LNG) to various European countries, which became foundational to its economic and diplomatic relations with Europe. This strategic use of energy reserves not only fostered economic benefits but also served as an instrument of diplomatic influence, embedding Qatar within the European energy discourse and affecting security and policy deliberations among EU member states.
A principal aspect of Qatar's influence in the European energy sector is its role as a major LNG exporter. Qatar has become a critical supplier of NLG to the European market, which has been increasingly seeking cleaner energy alternatives. Qatar's exports to Europe are managed through long-term contracts and adaptable supply agreements, ensuring a reliable and diversified energy source for European countries. For example, QatarEnergy signed long-term agreements with ConocoPhillips for LNG deliveries to Germany.
Beyond LNG exports, Qatar has entered into several strategic partnerships with European energy companies and governments. These partnerships often involve joint ventures, technological exchanges, and collaborative projects aimed at enhancing energy efficiency, exploring renewable energy opportunities, and developing new gas fields. Through these collaborations, Qatar seeks to solidify its position as a key player in Europe's energy landscape while supporting the continent's energy transition goals.
Qatar's investment in Europe extends to critical energy infrastructure, including terminals for LNG reception, storage facilities, and pipelines. These investments are crucial for ensuring the efficient transportation and distribution of natural gas across the continent. By investing in energy infrastructure, Qatar not only secures its export routes but also contributes to the development of a more integrated and resilient European energy network. Qatar currently exports about one-third of its LNG to Europe, with the United Kingdom, Belgium, Italy, and France also receiving significant volumes.


=== Real estate ===
One of the most visible aspects of Qatar's investments in Europe is in the real estate sector. QIA has acquired significant assets in major European cities. One of the most visible indicators of Qatar's presence in the European real estate market is its acquisition of iconic properties and luxury real estate. In London, Qatar's investment portfolio includes prestigious landmarks such as The Shard, Europe's tallest skyscraper, and the Harrods department store, one of the world's most famous luxury shopping destinations. Similarly, in Paris, Qatar owns significant stakes in luxury hotels and historic buildings, underscoring its interest in high-value, high-profile real estate assets.
An analysis revealed that the number of properties in London owned by individuals from Qatar increased by nearly 50% from 2018 to 2021, comprising 21.5 percent of all London properties held by Qatari buyers. Qatar's real estate investments in Europe have significant economic and political implications. Economically, these investments contribute to the development and dynamism of the European real estate market, bringing in capital and potentially driving up property values. Politically, the investments can be seen as part of Qatar's broader strategy to forge strong bilateral relations with key European nations, using economic ties to enhance diplomatic and strategic partnerships. Critics argue that significant foreign investments in strategic sectors or iconic properties could give countries like Qatar undue influence over local markets and policies.


=== Strategic Investments ===
One of the emerging focal points of Qatari investment in Europe is the biotech and technology sectors. Recognizing the potential for high returns and the strategic importance of innovation, the QIA has been actively positioning itself within the European biotech ecosystem. This includes investments in cutting-edge research and development projects that promise to drive advancements in healthcare, renewable energy, and digital technologies.
France and Germany rank as the second and third largest recipients of Qatari investments in Europe, with an estimate of $27 billion and $24 billion. In France, similar to its investment strategy in the UK, Qatar has acquired significant holdings in luxury real estate in Paris and has taken equity positions in a diverse array of leading French companies. These include Lagardère, a major media group; TotalEnergies, an oil giant; EADS, an aerospace conglomerate; Veolia, a utility firm; Areva, a nuclear power producer;Accor, a leading hospitality group, and more. In Germany, Qatar has established a significant presence as the largest shareholder of the Volkswagen Group. Additionally, Qatar holds stakes in Siemens, a major technology firm; Deutsche Bank, a leading financial institution; Hapag-Lloyd, a prominent shipping company; and Hochtief, a construction giant.
Qatar's investment activities in Europe have drawn severe criticism, encompassing issues from claims of receiving unfairly privileged treatment through tax exemptions to more serious accusations of human rights abuses, money laundering, and terrorism financing. These concerns highlight the complex and often contentious nature of significant foreign investments, especially those involving strategic sectors and sensitive political contexts.
The rationale behind Qatar's extensive investment in Europe is twofold. Firstly, it aims to diversify its investment portfolio and reduce its dependency on oil and gas revenues. Secondly, it seeks to establish Qatar as a key player in the global economy, capable of influencing economic trends and developments. By investing in Europe, Qatar gains access to some of the world's most developed markets, offering stability and potential for growth, and creating long-term economic ties with other powerful economies.
A notable example of Qatar's investment strategy in Europe is its commitment to invest $5 billion in Spain's EU-funded recovery projects. This investment underscores Qatar's interest in supporting European economies while securing lucrative opportunities for its sovereign wealth fund. Spain, with its diverse economy and strategic location, presents an attractive destination for Qatari investments, ranging from infrastructure and energy to technology and tourism.


== Qatar and European sports ==
Qatar's involvement in European sports, particularly football, is considered a prominent example of Qatars strategic use of soft power to enhance its global standing. Hosting significant events like the FIFA World Cup has played a crucial role in this strategy. Despite the significant financial burden, Qatar views these events as opportunities to enhance its international image and attract further investment and tourism, aligning with its long-term economic diversification goals.
A key element of Qatar's influence in European sports is its ownership and sponsorship of football clubs. The acquisition of Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) by QSI in 2011 stands as a prominent example. This investment has significantly elevated PSG's status, making it one of the richest and most successful clubs in Europe, capable of attracting elite players and securing numerous domestic championships. Additionally, Qatar has extended its sports sponsorship beyond PSG, establishing agreements with various European football leagues and branching into other sports through major Qatari companies such as Qatar Airways and the telecommunications firm Ooredoo.
Qatar's influence in European sports extends to the broadcasting sector, particularly through its ownership of beIN Sports, a global sports network. This network holds the broadcasting rights for key European football leagues and competitions across various regions, including the Middle East and North Africa (MENA). Among the competitions covered are the UEFA Champions League, UEFA Europa League, and the UEFA Europa Conference League, broadcast in multiple languages such as Arabic, English, and French across all 24 MENA countries. The broadcasting agreement emphasizes beIN Sports' significant role in distributing European football in this region but also enhances its influence over how the sport is presented to a global audience.
In 2017, beIN Sports television channels were banned in Saudi Arabia during a four-year blockade initiated by a Saudi-led coalition against Qatar, citing Qatar's alleged links to Islamist groups, such as al-Qaeda. The conflict escalated when a Saudi-led consortium attempted to purchase Newcastle United, a move opposed by beIN Sports due to its ownership of regional Premier League broadcasting rights. The blockade lasted until January 2021, when it was resolved, allowing for a restoration of relations.
Qatar's sports sponsorship strategy extends beyond club ownership including sponsorships of prestigious tournaments and competitions, offering Qatar an opportunity to promote itself as a destination for major sports events, leading up to the FIFA World Cup 2022 hosted by Qatar. PSG soccer star Neymar Jr., for example, became a global brand ambassador for Qatar National Bank (QNB). As part of the deal, Neymar will exclusively feature in the bank's marketing campaigns and appearances. QNB, a major sponsor of Paris Saint-Germain (PSG), funded Neymar's record-breaking transfer to the club in 2017. In August of last year, QSI financed Neymar's historic transfer from Barcelona to PSG, amounting to a staggering €222 million. Subsequently, the transaction has faced heightened scrutiny, with various reports indicating PSG's potential exploitation of owner-funded sponsorship agreements to navigate around UEFA's Financial Fair Play regulations.
Allegations of corruption and undue influence have surfaced, particularly in relation to FIFA's decision to award Qatar the hosting rights for the 2022 World Cup. Critics argue that such strategies aim to divert attention from domestic issues or project a certain image internationally, while proponents see them as legitimate efforts to participate in and contribute to global sports and culture. In addition, Critics have raised concerns about the implications of state-owned entities investing heavily in European clubs and leagues, questioning the impact on competition integrity and the potential for political leverage. Additionally, the issue of "sportswashing" has been highlighted, with accusations that Qatar is using its sports investments to distract from criticisms of its human rights record and labor practices.


=== The 2022 FIFA World Cup ===
The 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar has drawn considerable attention not only for being the first hosted in a majority-Muslim country but also for the influence Qatar exerted in the realms of sports and politics through the event. According to sources, this World Cup was part of Qatar's broader strategy to enhance its global standing and influence through "soft power". The event also served to project Qatar's cultural values and national identity to a global audience, in part by adhering to Islamic cultural norms such as restricting alcohol sales in stadiums.
The process by which Qatar was awarded the World Cup was steeped in controversy, with allegations of corruption and bribery. Critics argued that Qatar used its considerable financial resources to influence the voting process within FIFA. There were accusations by European and United States representatives that Qatari officials offered financial incentives to key football figures and nations to secure their votes, which Qatar has consistently denied.
In addition, Qatar faced criticism for its strict laws regarding alcohol consumption and LGBT rights, which are in stark contrast to the norms in many Western countries. The country's policies and attitudes toward these issues led to concerns about the safety and freedom of international visitors coming to the World Cup.


== Diplomatic relations ==
With significant financial resources but limited human resources, Qatar's leaders have used personal connections and strategic support for intermediaries as their main approach to foreign policy. Qatar's diplomatic relations with European countries are characterized by an interplay of mutual interests, strategic partnerships, and evolving geopolitical dynamics. These relations are underpinned by a shared interest in maintaining stability in the Middle East, energy security, and economic cooperation, alongside dialogue on human rights and labor practices. Qatar has actively sought to strengthen its diplomatic ties with European nations through high-level visits, strategic dialogues, and participation in international forums. These engagements are aimed at fostering mutual understanding, exploring areas of cooperation, and addressing global challenges such as terrorism, climate change, and regional conflicts. Qatar's diplomacy is informed by its desire to be a mediator in the Middle East, offering its good offices to facilitate peace talks and conflict resolution, a role that has been recognized and appreciated by many European countries.
Recent years have seen significant developments in Qatar's diplomatic relations with European countries and its neighbors in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC). Qatar has established a series of bilateral agreements and strategic dialogues with various European nations, aiming to strengthen cooperation across multiple sectors. For example, France's relationship with Qatar is marked by the establishment of a Strategic Dialogue in 2019. This framework facilitates operational follow-up on major projects that structure the bilateral relationship, encompassing defense, energy, investment, and cultural exchanges. In addition, in April 2023, France welcomed the announcement that Qatar and Bahrain had resumed diplomatic relations and reopened embassies, marking a positive step towards regional stability.
Human rights and labor practices, particularly the Kafala system, have been points of contention in Qatar's relations with European countries. European nations have consistently called for reforms to improve labor conditions and protect the rights of migrant workers in Qatar. In response, Qatar has implemented a series of reforms aimed at addressing these concerns, including the partial dismantling of the Kafala system. These efforts are part of a broader dialogue on human rights between Qatar and its European partners, reflecting a commitment to addressing international concerns.
The criticism of Qatar in Europe itself has been subject to scrutiny, with some observers pointing out perceived hypocrisy and racism in the European response. Accusations of bias and double standards have been raised, noting that similar issues in other countries have not always elicited the same level of outrage. Some claim that Qatar and other Muslim states may apply different sets of principles depending on their interests, highlighting the complex interplay of ethical stances, geopolitical interests, and historical grievances. In the Ukraine conflict, for example, Qatar emphasizes that sovereignty is a "redline" in its discussions about Ukraine. Despite this stance, Qatar continues to engage with Russia, particularly regarding global energy markets. This demonstrates Qatar's problematic approach to maintaining its interests in global energy, even while holding a principled stance on national sovereignty.
Qatar's alleged involvement in influence campaigns and political lobbying within European institutions has also been a source of controversy. The "Qatargate" scandal, involving accusations of corruption and influence-peddling within the European Parliament, has highlighted concerns about the transparency and integrity of Qatar's political engagements in Europe. The organization emphasized that this isn't an isolated incident but part of a larger issue of ethics and transparency within the European Parliament, suggesting that the institution has long suffered from a "culture of impunity". Critics argue that such activities undermine democratic processes and could potentially skew policy decisions in favor of Qatar's interests.
The scandal erupted when several current and former Members of the European Parliament were arrested on charges of corruption, accepting bribes in the form of large sums of money and significant gifts from Qatari representatives. This was purportedly in exchange for influencing parliamentary decisions and legislation favorable to Qatar. This has led to a significant backlash, with the European Parliament suspending access to its premises for Qatari representatives and halting all pending legislation involving Qatar as investigations continue. Transparency International, an NGO, has labeled this scandal as "the most blatant case of alleged corruption witnessed by the European Parliament in many years".
Qatar's political soft power is also rooted in its extensive network of foreign relationships. Qatar's foreign policy of maintaining relations with various groups has faced criticism, with accusations that the state is a major financial supporter of 'terrorist' organizations. Qatar has developed a reputation for supporting various Islamist groups across the Middle East, from Hamas and groups in Syria and Libya to the Taliban. This has sometimes led to perceptions of Qatar as a promoter of Islamist agendas.


== Culture and education ==

European educational institutions have established a notable presence in Qatar. Universities such as University College London and HEC Paris have opened campuses in Qatar, as part of Qatar's education city program, offering programs in fields ranging from museum studies to business administration. These institutions attract students from around the world, leveraging Qatar's strategic location and its investments in education to serve as a bridge between Western and Eastern educational practices.
However, the involvement of European schools in Qatar has not been without controversy. Instances involving the leadership of French educational institutions in Qatar highlight some of the challenges faced. For example, Hafid Adnani, the former headmaster of the Bonaparte French School of Doha, was dismissed and required to leave the country following a dispute with the school's financial director, who accused Adnani of lying about his credentials and expressing anti-Muslim sentiments. This incident raised questions about cultural and administrative clashes in international educational ventures.
Further complicating the scenario, Franck Choinard, another headmaster from the Voltaire French School, was forced out under troubling circumstances, accused of paedophilia, an allegation he denied. The underlying issues reportedly stemmed from conflicts over the curriculum that pitted the Qatari authorities against the secular board managing the school. These incidents illustrate the delicate balance required when foreign educational policies and practices meet local cultural and regulatory frameworks, often leading to misunderstandings and conflicts.


== Media influence ==

Qatar's strategic investments in European media are driven by several key factors, encompassing both financial gains and geopolitical influence. Qatar's media ventures in Europe, such as its ownership stakes in Al Jazeera and the launch of Al Arabiya TV in London, are part of a broader strategy to influence cultural and political discourse. Al Jazeera, known for its extensive global reach, has expanded into European markets, strengthening Qatar's presence in international media. Additionally, Al Arabiya TV targets Arabic-speaking youth in Europe, further extending Qatar's media influence. They provide Qatar with a platform to promote narratives that align with its interests, influence public opinion, and participate in cultural exchange. However, this has also raised concerns about potential biases and the impact on editorial independence within European media. The presence of Qatari investments has sparked discussions about the balance between necessary financial support for media outlets and safeguarding against undue foreign influence.


=== Al Jazeera ===
Qatar's influence in the global media landscape is significant, particularly through its flagship media enterprise, Al Jazeera. Founded by the Qatari royal family in 1996, Al Jazeera is a global news network broadcasting in Arabic, English, and several other languages. The network serves as a medium for Qatar to reach international audiences. However, it notably refrains from scrutinize the royal family's associations with various groups such as Hamas.
Due to its ties to the royal family, Al Jazeera operates with a degree of financial independence uncommon among other cable news networks, which are typically subject to market pressures. This has allowed it to serve as an alternative to the often censored state media in the region, focusing on reporting popular grievances and protest movements. This approach has upset powerful regimes such as Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Egypt, and Bahrain, which accuse Al Jazeera of inciting terrorism. Al Jazeera, however, contends that these accusations are attempts to stifle free expression in the region.
Since the launch of Al Jazeera English in 2006, the network has established a robust presence across the European continent, offering in-depth coverage of European affairs and providing alternative perspectives on global news. With broadcast centers in London and other European cities, the network has been able to cover European news with a depth and breadth that rivals many domestic European news outlets. Al Jazeera's bureaus across Europe, from the Balkans to Scandinavia, enable it to report on a wide range of issues, from political developments and economic crises to social movements and cultural trends. Al Jazeera has gained a reputation among European audiences for its comprehensive coverage of the Middle East, offering insights that often challenge the narratives presented by Western media. Its coverage of events such as the Arab Spring and the Syrian conflict has been particularly noted for providing a platform to voices that are less heard in mainstream European media.
Al Jazeera has faced controversies and criticisms. According to BBC, "Al-Jazeera network remains the standard bearer for the Islamist position". Some governments and critics have accused the network of bias, particularly in its coverage of Middle Eastern politics. These accusations often stem from the network's willingness to broadcast dissenting viewpoints, which has led to tensions with various countries. Additionally, Al Jazeera's ties to the Qatari government have raised questions about its editorial independence, although the network maintains that it operates with journalistic autonomy.


==== The case of Yusuf al-Qaradawi ====
Yusuf al-Qaradawi was a prominent Egyptian Islamic theologian known for his extensive work in contemporary Islamic thought and his influential role in the Muslim Brotherhood. He passed away in 2022, but his impact and legacy in the Islamic world remain significant. Al-Qaradawi was born in Egypt in 1926 and became involved with the Muslim Brotherhood in his youth. His academic achievements in Islamic theology earned him a high profile in religious circles. He was known for trying to reconcile Islamic traditionalism with modernity, advocating for what he saw as a moderate interpretation of Islam that was both progressive and adaptable to the challenges of modern life.
He was incarcerated during Egypt's monarchical period due to his anti-British activities and was imprisoned three times under Nasser's rule for his affiliations with the Muslim Brotherhood. In 1963, he fled to Qatar, where he became a citizen in 1968, eventually emerging as a leading global Islamic scholar. Residing in Qatar for many years after being exiled from Egypt, al-Qaradawi found a receptive base for his activities and a platform from which he could reach a global audience, particularly through the Qatar-based Al Jazeera network. This relationship allowed him to disseminate his views widely and positioned Qatar as a critical player in the realm of Islamic discourse.
Qatar's support for al-Qaradawi brought Qatar under scrutiny and criticism. Al-Qaradawi's controversial positions, especially his support for what he considered resistance efforts against oppression, aligned with Qatar's own complex and sometimes contentious foreign policy. For instance, his endorsement of groups like Hamas, his support for Palestinian suicide bombings and his outspoken views on conflicts in the Middle East, reflected a bold stance that often conflicted with the policies and sentiments of Western nations and some Arab states.
This alignment with al-Qaradawi thus had dual effects: it bolstered Qatar's image as a significant Islamic intellectual hub, but it also attracted accusations of supporting extremism, particularly from neighboring countries like Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Egypt, and Bahrain. These nations, which have had strained relations with Qatar, particularly pointed to Qatar's support for figures like al-Qaradawi as evidence of its problematic foreign policy.


== Security and terrorism ==
Qatar has engaged in significant military and defense collaboration with several European countries. This includes joint training exercises, defense procurement, and strategic dialogues aimed at enhancing military capabilities and interoperability. Qatar's purchases of military hardware from European defense contractors not only bolster its own defense posture but also strengthen defense industrial ties with Europe. Additionally, Qatar hosts military bases that serve as strategic assets for Western allies, including the United States, which further cements its role as a key security partner in the region.
In the face of growing cyber threats, Qatar has prioritized cybersecurity cooperation with European partners. This includes sharing best practices, collaborating on cyber defense strategies, and participating in international efforts to combat cybercrime. The exchange of information and expertise in this area is vital for protecting critical infrastructure and ensuring the security of digital communications. Qatar and several European countries have collaborated on security preparations for major events, such as the FIFA World Cup 2022, highlighting the importance of international security partnerships.
Qatar's security cooperation with Europe in the realm of counter-terrorism is controversial. Qatar and European nations share intelligence, collaborate on law enforcement efforts, and work together to combat the financing of terrorism. Qatar's role in mediating conflicts and its diplomatic ties with a wide range of actors in the Middle East position it as a valuable partner in efforts to address the root causes of terrorism and violent extremism.
Qatar's involvement in counter terrorism is controversial as they are also considered a significant supporter and financer of numerous terrorist groups such as Al-Qaeda, Hamas, Hezbollah and Islamic State of Iraq and Syria (ISIS). Between 2012 and 2015 multiple reports suggested that Qatar was backing the Al Nusra Front, recognized as a terrorist organization and the Syrian branch of Al-Qaeda by the US in 2012. Notable publications such as the Wall Street Journal and the New York Times highlighted occasions when Al Nusra leaders visiting Doha and concerns voiced by President Obama to Qatari leadership about arming extremists. In addition, reports from the Washington Post in 2015 indicated that Qatar played a role in forming the “Army of Conquest,” a coalition where Al Nusra was a significant participant.
Qatar has a history of supporting Hamas, a designated as a terrorist organization by Israel, the United States, European Union, Canada, Egypt and Japan. Qatar has provided financial aid, estimated at $1.8 billion over the years, political support. In addition, Qatar has also hosted Hamas officials including Ismail Haniyeh and Khaled Mashal and provided them with a political platform. Qatar's support has positioned it as a key negotiator in conflicts between Hamas and Israel, despite questions about its neutrality due to its ongoing relationship with Hamas. While the Qatari government is not directly funding ISIS, there have been concerns about private individuals in Qatar contributing to the group. The U.S. has noted that Qatar could be seen as a permissive environment for the financing of extremist groups, and although significant steps have been taken to improve its counter-terrorism financing laws, challenges remain in fully curbing the flow of private funds from Qatar to groups like ISIS.


=== The Muslim brotherhood ===
This funding strategy aligns with Qatar's broader foreign policy objectives, which appear to be aimed at expanding its influence within Islamic communities in Europe. Investigations and reports have shown that Qatar has been a major funder of Muslim Brotherhood-affiliated projects across Europe. European governments have expressed concerns about this involvement, particularly wary of the potential for radicalization and the creation of isolated communities that may not integrate well with broader European society. The Muslim Brotherhood's ideological stance and its implications for integration and security remain contentious issues in European political and social spheres.
"Qatar Papers" by French journalists Georges Malbrunot and Christian Chesnot uncovers Qatar's extensive funding of the Muslim Brotherhood (MB) in Europe, particularly through financial contributions aimed at spreading Islamist ideology. The book, based on a wide range of documents and testimonies across its 295 pages and 14 chapters, discusses how over the past eight years Qatar funded over 140 projects in Europe to spread MB ideology.
The authors provide detailed accounts of how funds were distributed, including €72 million funneled directed to influential figures within the MB network in seven European countries. Notably, the book details how Tariq Ramadan, a prominent but controversial MB figure in Europe, received a substantial consultancy fee of €35,000 per month from the Qatar Foundation. Furthermore, just before his arrest on charges unrelated to the funding, Ramadan withdrew a large sum of €590,000 from Qatari bank accounts, underscoring his deep financial ties with Qatar. In addition, the book reveals a strategic document found in the Swiss home of Youssef Nada, a key MB leader, which outlines plans to influence European local governments and officials. This strategy was aimed at increasing the MB's ideological influence through local governance.
"Qatar Papers" also highlights French intelligence concerns regarding Qatari support for the Union des Organisations Islamiques de France, a key umbrella group in France known for its MB affiliations. Beyond individuals and political strategies, the book exposes Qatari funding of institutions like Mucivi, or the Musée des Civilisations de l'Islam in Geneva, which is accused of promoting MB propaganda.


== See also ==
Qatar corruption scandal at the European Parliament


== Further reading ==
Antwi-Boateng, O. (2013). The rise of Qatar as a soft power and challenges. European scientific journal, 9(10), 39–51.
Chestnot, C., & Malbrunot, G. (2024). How Qatar became an actor in the spread of political Islam in Europe. In handbook of political Islam in Europe: Activities, Means, and Strategies from Salafists to the Muslim Brotherhood and beyond (pp. 205–215). Cham: Springer international publishing
Chestnot, C., & Malbrunot, G. (2020). Qatar Papers: How Doha finances the Muslim Brotherhood in Europe.

title: Muhammad Fhirdan Guntara
content:
Muhammad Fhirdan Maulana Guntara (born 2 September 1998) is an Indonesian professional basketball player for the Prawira Bandung of the Indonesian Basketball League (IBL).


== Early career ==
Represented the West Java province and won the gold medal for basketball at the 2016 Pekan Olahraga Nasional .


== College career ==
Fhirdan played college basketball for  the ITHB Arrows alongside his current teammate Yudha, and they both won the LIMA championship in 2019.


== Personal ==
Fhirdan has an older brother, Reza. They used to play alongside before he left Prawira to play for Pelita Jaya Bakrie.
